│ THOUGHT: The issue is that LLVM's instcombine pass is incorrectly           │
│ transforming a select with fcmp ole (ordered less than or equal) into an    │
│ fabs intrinsic. The problem occurs with signaling NaN (SNaN) values. When x │
│ is SNaN (#xfc80), the original code returns SNaN, but the transformed code  │
│ returns a different SNaN (#x7c80). The issue is that fcmp ole with SNaN     │
│ should return false (since SNaN is unordered), so the select chooses the    │
│ original x value (SNaN), but fabs canonicalizes SNaN to a quiet NaN or      │
│ changes its sign bit. The transformation is only valid when we can          │
│ guarantee no NaN values or when the function has nnan (no NaN) fast math    │
│ flags. I need to find where this transformation is implemented and add a    │
│ check for NaN handling.                                                     │
│                                                                             │
│ ```bash                                                                     │
│ find /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm -name "*.cpp" | xargs grep -l             │
│ "select.*fcmp.*fabs\|fabs.*select.*fcmp" 2>/dev/null                        │
│ ```                                                                         │
